# Game/Replay/AnimateMergeHand.elm — EARLY

Replay animation driver for MergeHand — one of two async
hand-origin animators (with `AnimatePlaceHand`) extracted
as REFACTOR_ELM_REPLAY B1/Axis Y, 2026-04-22.

Hand-origin primitives don't ship with a captured gesture
path (they cross the board widget boundary, so viewport coords
at capture time would be meaningless at replay time if the
board scrolled or the window resized). Replay instead
synthesizes a linear path after asking the DOM for the hand
card's live viewport rect.

## Status

- **Label:** EARLY. Two-phase interface (prepare / finish)
  reflects the async handshake with the DOM. The shape is
  identical between AnimateMergeHand and AnimatePlaceHand
  except for how each computes the target endpoint —
  stack edge for this one, explicit `loc` for the other.

## Interface

```elm
type alias PrepareResult =
    { source : DragSource
    , grabOffset : Point
    , handCardToMeasure : Card
    }

prepare : { handCard, target, side } -> Model -> Maybe PrepareResult

finish :
    { handCard, target, side }
    -> Point       -- origin from DOM
    -> Float       -- nowMs
    -> DragSource  -- from the stashed AwaitingHandRect ctx
    -> Point       -- grabOffset, ditto
    -> Model
    -> Maybe Space.AnimationInfo
```

`prepare` returns Nothing when the hand card isn't present
in the active hand (contract violation). `finish` returns
Nothing when the target stack drifted off the board between
prepare and rect-arrival — shouldn't happen in practice
within one animation frame but is kept total.

## Dependencies

- `Game.Replay.Space` — for `handCardSource`,
  `stackEdgeInLiveViewport`, `linearPath`, `AnimationInfo`.
- `Game.CardStack` — for `findStack` (target resolution).
- `Game.BoardActions` — for `Side`.
- `Game.WireAction` — for `WA.MergeHand`.
- `Main.State` — for `Model`, `DragSource`, `PathFrame`,
  `Point`.

## Pointers

- Called from `Game.Replay.Time.prepareHandAnim` /
  `finishHandAnim` — the two dispatchers route hand-origin
  WireActions to this module or `AnimatePlaceHand`.
- Board-origin siblings: `AnimateSplit`, `AnimateMergeStack`,
  `AnimateMoveStack` (all synchronous, one-phase).
